|Section3={{Chembox Structure | CrystalStruct = | SpaceGroup = | LattConst_a = | LattConst_b = | LattConst_c = | LattConst_beta = | UnitCellVolume = | UnitCellFormulas = | LattConst_Comment = }} |Section7={{Chembox Hazards | ExternalSDS = | EUClass = | RPhrases = | SPhrases = | NFPA-H = 0 | NFPA-F = 2 | NFPA-R = | NFPA-S = <!-- 1 ? --> | FlashPtC = 83 | AutoignitionPtC = | ExploLimits = | PEL = | REL = | IDLH = | LC50 = }} }} '''Tetrahydrofurfuryl acetate''' is an organic chemical compound used for food flavouring and cosmetics. It has a fruity ethereal flavour,<ref name="Burdock1997">{{cite book|last=Burdock|first=George A.|title=Encyclopedia of Food and Color Additives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vxtxWneRBN4C&pg=PA2758+|accessdate=17 January 2017|date=1997|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=9780849394126|pages=2758–}}</ref> also described as honey, maple, or bread-like.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/food/food-safety-quality/scientific-advice/jecfa/jecfa-flav/details/en/c/1430/|title=Food safety and quality: details|work=[[Food and Agriculture Organization]]|accessdate=17 January 2017}}</ref>
It is generally accepted as safe in the USA.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Administration|first1=Food and Drug|last2=(U.S.)|first2=Office of the Federal Register|title=The Code of Federal Regulations of the United States of America|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|page=54|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Vu48AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA54|language=en|year=2001}}</ref> Typical levels of use are 2 ppm in drinks, 8 ppm in icecream, and 20 ppm in baked products and confectionery.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Food Protection Committee - National Academy of Sciences|title=Chemicals Used in Food Processing|date=1965|publisher=National Academies|page=195|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=o5ErAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA292|language=en}}</ref>
Chemically, it is a heterocyclic ester. It is made by reacting tetrahydrofurfuryl alcohol with [[acetic anhydride]].<ref name=fen/>
Related flavouring compounds are tetrahydrofurfuryl butyrate, tetrahydrofurfuryl cinnamate, tetrahydrofurfuryl alcohol,<ref name=fen>{{cite book|last1=Fenaroli|first1=Giovanni|last2=Furia|first2=Thomas E.|last3=Bellanca|first3=Nicoló|title=Fenaroli's Handbook of Flavor Ingredients|date=1975|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=9780878195336|page=529|edition=2|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=fbnVjdBvFlkC&pg=PA529|language=en}}</ref> and tetrahydrofurfuryl propionate.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Maga|first1=Joseph A.|last2=Katz|first2=Ira|title=Furans in foods|journal=C R C Critical Reviews in Food Science and Nutrition|date=May 1979|volume=11|issue=4|pages=355–400|doi=10.1080/10408397909527268}}</ref>
